   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>All in
                           the Wrong</title></hi>].<note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>All in the Wrong</title>; A Comedy, In Five Acts; By
                                 <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Arthur Murphy</ref>, Esq. As
                              Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane"
                                 >Drury Lane</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers From
                              the Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs"
                                 >Mrs. Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman,
                        Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays,
                              Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and
                              Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. XV. <hi
                           rendition="#italics">
                           <title><ref target="people.html#BarbarossaAruj"
                           >Barbarossa</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Way to
                              Keep Him</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>All in the
                              Wrong</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Grecian
                              Daughter</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Know Your Own
                              Mind</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme,
                        Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged at the
                           <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref> on
                        June 15<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1761. Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters
                        edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism
                        Archive</hi>.</note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>The author of this excellent comedy was a man of learning, whose propensity to the
               drama ruined his better prospects. He was called to the bar by the Society of
               Lincoln's Inn, but practised the law with so little fervency, compared to the ardour
               with which he pursued dramatic writing, that, when this prevailing taste subsided,
               and he could no longer excite his Muse to her wonted labour, he found himself
               suddenly reduced to a state of poverty, which no after discretion could
                  counteract.<note>In 1757, <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> was
                  accepted into The Honourable Society of Lincoln's Inn, one of the four
                  professional associations for barristers in England and Wales. He was then
                  admitted to the bar in 1762 and practiced law until 1788; however, he continued
                  writing plays throughout this time, never fully devoting himself to either
                  profession. Despite the income from his writings and law practice, <ref
                     target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> lived beyond his means and was
                  frequently in debt.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Mr. Murphy</ref>'s dramatic works are
               numerous, but they were produced at a period when an author's profits were but small;
               and though he had no vices to plunge him into indigence, he was habituated to the
               domestic conveniencies of a gentleman, and he had not strength of mind to yield up
               the ease and elegance, which affluence alone should bestow, for the content and pride
               of freedom and independence. But to reproach the present author with a weakness,
               common to men of letters as well as to the illiterate, would be treating him harshly,
               according to the rules of custom, though with perfect justice, according to the
               principles of honour and fortitude.</p>

            <p>Amongst his number of dramatic productions, the present play of "<title>All in the
                  Wrong</title>" ranks as one of <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b
                  2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/>the best. In his Prologue, or Preface, he acknowledges
               himself indebted to <ref target="people.html#Moliere">Moliere</ref> for some of his
                  scenes.<note>In the "Advertisement" prefacing the first edition of this play, <ref
                     target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> writes: "The first hint of this
                  Comedy was suggested by the <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Cocu
                        Imaginaire</title></hi> of <ref target="people.html#Moliere">Moliere</ref>,
                  who took the idea of his piece from an italian writer." <ref
                     target="people.html#Moliere">Moliere</ref>'s 1660 one-act comedy <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Sganarelle, ou Le Cocu Imaginaire</title></hi> (<hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Sganarelle, or The Imaginary Cuckold</title></hi>)
                  was influenced by the traditions of French farce and the Italian commedia
                  dell'arte.</note>
               <ref target="people.html#Moliere">Moliere</ref>'s genius has been of use to many of
               our comic dramatists, who, at the time <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Mr.
                  Murphy</ref> wrote, enriched their works with his wit and humour, without calling
               themselves translators, but merely occasional debtors to his primary invention.</p>

            <p>It would be much advantage to English authors of the present time, to have such
               resource in a neighbouring nation now. Still, it requires no mean talent to dispose
               of borrowed goods to the advantage of the wearer; and when an incident is formed to
               ornament one drama, it is difficult to make it fit so nicely as to be an adornment to
               another.</p>

            <p>The dialogue of "<title>All in the Wrong</title>" is of a species so natural, that it
               never in one sentence soars above the proper standard of elegant life; and the
               incidents that occur are bold without extravagance or apparent artifice, which is the
               criterion on which judgment should be formed between comedy and farce.</p>

            <p>The last scene in the fourth act is an illustration of this position&#8212;its effect
               is comic to the highest degree, yet having arisen from causes consonant with the
               general events of life, no particle of burlesque infringes on the rational enjoyment,
               which an enlightened audience receives from the whimsical coincidence of unlooked-for
               accidents. A veil should now be substituted in this scene, for that old-fashioned
               appendage to disguise, a mask.<note>The action of the play centers around the mutual
                  jealousy of Sir John and Lady Restless. In Act IV, scene iv, Lady Restless, using
                  a mask, has disguised herself as "Mrs. Marmalet" and seduced Sir John. Sir John is
                  in the middle of proclaiming his love for "Mrs. Marmalet" and assuring her of his
                  hatred of his wife when Lady Restless unmasks herself. A quarrel ensues, in the
                  midst of which Sir John realizes that someone is hiding in the closet. Their
                  servant, Tattle, unlocks the closet to reveal their acquaintance Beverley, who had
                  come to the house to request Sir John return his painting. Tattle had hidden
                  Beverley in the closet for fear that Sir John would interpret Beverley's presence
                  as evidence of an affair with Lady Restless. Indeed, Sir John jumps to such
                  conclusion, using Beverley's presence to absolve himself of his tryst with "Mrs.
                  Marmalet." As the fight continues, both Sir John and Lady Restless claim that
                  their actions were aimed at curing the other of their suspicions. The
                  miscommunication persists, and the scene ends with the couple storming out of
                  different doors at opposite ends of the room.</note></p>

            <p>It was a hardy enterprize of the author to attempt the delineation of six jealous
               characters in the self-<pb n="5"/>same play; but difficult as the task was, he has
               succeeded in making an excellent comedy, though not six excellent parts. Clarissa and
               Young Bellmont are but faint shadows of the other four characters; and Beverley and
               Belinda are, in dramatic substance, greatly inferior to Sir John and Lady
                  Restless.<note>The subplot of the comedy revolves around the infectious jealousy
                  of the main pair that has spread to the relationships of their acquaintances, the
                  young lovers Beverley and Belinda and Clarissa and Young Bellmont.</note></p>

            <p>When the powers of invention forsook <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Mr.
                  Murphy</ref>,&#8212;with great credit to his sober judgment and remaining
               abilities,&#8212;he became the translator of <ref target="people.html#Tacitus"
                  >Tacitus</ref>.<note><ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> began
                  working on his translation of <ref target="people.html#Tacitus">Tacitus</ref> in
                  1767. He finally published <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Works of <ref
                           target="people.html#Tacitus">Cornelius Tacitus</ref>; with an Essay on
                        His Life and Genius</title></hi> in four volumes in 1793. Two of his later
                  plays, <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Zenobia</title></hi> (1768) and <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Arminius</title></hi> (1798), were largely taken
                  from <ref target="people.html#Tacitus">Tacitus</ref>' work.</note> When all
               exertion of a writer was fled, <ref target="people.html#WedderburnAlexander">Lord
                  Loughborough</ref>, his former acquaintance, and then <ref
                  target="people.html#WedderburnAlexander">Chancellor of England</ref>, gave him a
               place as Commissioner of Bankrupts;&#8212;and, when the infirmity of age bereft him
               of bodily force to act in this capacity, the <ref
                  target="people.html#GeorgeIIIKingofGreatBritain">King</ref>, in his gracious
               benevolence, allowed him an annuity of three hundred a year, which snatched him from
               bitter penury, and retarded, whilst it smoothed, his passage to the
                  grave.<note>Through his acquaintance with <ref
                     target="people.html#WedderburnAlexander">Lord Loughborough</ref>, <ref
                     target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> was made Commissioner of
                  Bankruptcy in 1803. Beginning in 1798, <ref
                     target="people.html#GeorgeIIIKingofGreatBritain">King George III</ref> had
                  granted him a pension of £200 per year, which he continued to collect to the end
                  of his life.</note></p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw>
         </div>
      </body>
